The reason why using a size_t instead of socklen_t is related to endianness is that on a big endian system, we would store the MSB bytes first, and so when we reinterpret a 64 bit size_t to a 32 bit socklen_t and pass that to a socklen_t pointer, the function would just store the result in the 4 bytes that the pointer points to. This result when we read the entire 64 bit size_t variable would be a value that is left shifted by 32 bits. To get the proper result here, we would need to right shift by 32 times. (Note that on little endian systems, the other 4 bytes which are hopefully zeroed would not change the length when considering it as a 64 bit field.)

It would definitely help to be able to run our tests on big endian systems, not sure how feasible that is.
@nicolasnoble Can we add that?
